# Visualize the data before modeling
ggplot(Boston) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = medv)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of House Values",
       x = "Median Value ($1000s)",
       y = "Count")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# Create a binary target for classification (1 if above median, 0 otherwise)
Boston$expensive <- as.factor(ifelse(Boston$medv > median(Boston$medv), 1, 0))

# Look at class balance
table(Boston$expensive)
## 
##   0   1 
## 256 250
# Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123)
train_indices <- createDataPartition(Boston$medv, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- Boston[train_indices, ]
test_data <- Boston[-train_indices, ]

# Function to calculate RMSE
rmse <- function(actual, predicted) {
  sqrt(mean((actual - predicted)^2))
}

# 1. Generalized Additive Model (GAM)
gam_model <- gam(medv ~ s(lstat) + s(rm) + s(dis) + s(nox)+ s(ptratio) +s(crim), data = train_data)
gam_predictions <- predict(gam_model, newdata = test_data)
gam_rmse <- rmse(test_data$medv, gam_predictions)

# 2. Random Forest
# For regression
rf_model <- randomForest(medv ~ . - expensive, data = train_data)
rf_predictions <- predict(rf_model, newdata = test_data)
rf_rmse <- rmse(test_data$medv, rf_predictions)

# For classification
rf_class_model <- randomForest(expensive ~ . - medv, data = train_data)
rf_class_predictions <- predict(rf_class_model, newdata = test_data)
rf_accuracy <- mean(rf_class_predictions == test_data$expensive)

# 3. Logistic Regression
# Prepare the data
x_train <- model.matrix(expensive ~ . - medv - 1, data = train_data)
y_train <- train_data$expensive
x_test <- model.matrix(expensive ~ . - medv - 1, data = test_data)

logistic_model <- glmnet(x_train, y_train, family = "binomial", alpha = 0)
logistic_predictions <- predict(logistic_model, newx = x_test, type = "response", s = 0.01)
logistic_class <- ifelse(logistic_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)
logistic_accuracy <- mean(logistic_class == test_data$expensive)

# 4. Support Vector Machine (SVM)
# For regression
svm_model <- svm(medv ~ . - expensive, data = train_data)
svm_predictions <- predict(svm_model, newdata = test_data)
svm_rmse <- rmse(test_data$medv, svm_predictions)

# For classification
svm_class_model <- svm(expensive ~ . - medv, data = train_data, probability = TRUE)
svm_class_predictions <- predict(svm_class_model, newdata = test_data)
svm_accuracy <- mean(svm_class_predictions == test_data$expensive)

# 5. Neural Network
# Fit the Neural Network model for classification
nn_model <- nnet(expensive ~ ., data = train_data, size = 5, decay = 0.01, maxit = 200)

# Predict class probabilities on the test dataset
nn_predictions_prob <- predict(nn_model, newdata = test_data, type = "raw")

# Convert probabilities to predicted classes
nn_predictions_class <- as.factor(ifelse(nn_predictions_prob > 0.5, 1, 0))

# Calculate accuracy
nn_accuracy <- mean(nn_predictions_class == test_data$expensive)

# ROC curves for classification models
rf_probs <- predict(rf_class_model, newdata = test_data, type = "prob")[,2]
logistic_probs <- as.vector(logistic_predictions)
svm_probs <- attr(predict(svm_class_model, newdata = test_data, probability = TRUE), "probabilities")[,2]
nn_probs <- as.numeric(nn_predictions_prob)

roc_rf <- roc(test_data$expensive, rf_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_logistic <- roc(test_data$expensive, logistic_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_svm <- roc(test_data$expensive, svm_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls > cases
roc_nn <- roc(test_data$expensive, nn_probs)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Plot ROC curves
plot(roc_rf, col = "red", main = "ROC Curves")
lines(roc_logistic, col = "blue")
lines(roc_svm, col = "green")
lines(roc_nn, col = "purple")
legend("bottomright", legend = c("Random Forest", "Logistic Regression", "SVM", "Neural Network"),
       col = c("red", "blue", "green", "purple"), lwd = 2)

# Feature importance for Random Forest
importance_rf <- importance(rf_model)
varImpPlot(rf_model, main = "Random Forest - Variable Importance")

importance_df <- data.frame(
  Feature = rownames(importance_rf),
  Importance = importance_rf[,1]
)
importance_df <- importance_df[order(-importance_df$Importance), ]

# Create the plot
ggplot(importance_df, aes(x = reorder(Feature, Importance), y = Importance)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Random Forest - Feature Importance",
       x = "Features",

    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
